Thank you everyone for the endless love. We have read every single message from all of you. It is so heartwarming to feel the love around you and such a hard time. Aziza is missed every second of every day. She has been by my side through Paralympic games, red carpets, 6 surgeries, 10 or 15 different countries, commercials, two times to The White HouseDancing with the Stars, hundreds of speaking events, hundreds of different mountains and so much more. I wake up every day missing her by my side. I know I will heal in time. Your endless love and support has really made my heart feel full.
rest in peace my sweet Aziza. I pray you’re getting cupcakes in heaven every day. I love and miss you. Thank you Aziza for being the heart of our family
#RIP 🐾 ❤️ ❤️‍🩹 #myangel

#FacingYourFears feel the fear and do it anyway. Do you have a bucket list? I do, and skydiving is at the top of my bucket list. This is some thing I fear just thinking of it gives me anxiety and makes my chest feel heavy. I may be afraid of falling but this is something I want to conquer. So I took the steps on making this a reality. You may think because I’m blind that it might be easier. It actually is harder! Not knowing where you are ,feeling all the other senses ,the wind in your ears - messing with your equilibrium… I’m up for the challenge to face my fear. Are you? Thank you to Ifly for giving me this experience and progression to overcoming my fears and checking this off my bucket list
what scares you the most?  This by far is my biggest fear. One day I will skydive and when I do I will have overcome one of my biggest fears in life.

🌟Fear of Change🌟

“I’ve recently found myself in deep reflection, triggered by meeting an incredible woman who’s currently navigating this journey with her own son. It’s made me ponder on my own experience as a parent and the transformative power of change.”

Change can be both exhilarating and terrifying. It’s astonishing to witness the person he is becoming, with each day bringing new discoveries, challenges, and triumphs. His laughter, his dreams, and his unbridled curiosity fill our home with boundless energy and love.

Yet, there’s a part of me that can’t help but feel the pang of nostalgia and the fear of letting go. The days of cradling him in my arms seem like a distant memory. Time is an artist, painting its masterpiece on the canvas of our lives, and it’s doing so with breathtaking speed.

As a parent, it’s natural to worry about the unknown path ahead. Will he be okay? Will I have prepared him enough for life’s inevitable twists and turns? 🤔

But in these moments of vulnerability, I remind myself that change is the essence of life. Just as the caterpillar transforms into a butterfly, our children too must evolve and spread their wings. It’s our role to be their guiding light, offering love, wisdom, and unwavering support.

So, while I may have a tinge of fear in my heart, I choose to embrace this journey with open arms and an open heart. Because change, as daunting as it can be, also promises growth, learning, and the beautiful evolution of the bonds we share.
I love you son. With my whole heart ❤️ 
To all the parents out there navigating the seas of change, remember that we are not alone in our emotions. Let’s cherish each moment, hold onto the memories, and look forward to the future with hope, for our children are destined for greatness.

#ParentingJourney #GrowingUp #EmbracingChange #UnconditionalLove ❤️👨‍👩‍👦🌼

Meet Danelle Umstead @danelleumstead : a living testament to the power of resilience and determination. If you’re looking for a keynote speaker who can inspire your audience to overcome challenges and embrace the highs in life, Danelle’s story is a must-hear. Diagnosed with multiple sclerosis, she faced her darkest challenge – half her body was paralyzed, and she had to relearn to walk. But within that struggle, she found her true passion: skiing.

🌟My Blindness🌟

I wanted to take a moment to open up and share a little piece of my world with you. You know, one of the most common things I hear is, “You don’t look blind!” 😄 Well, thank you, I think? LOL  I thought it might be helpful to describe what my blindness looks like in words.

Feel free to ask more questions below 👇 
In comments. I love the interaction and sharing. 

Imagine the Target logo. You know, that iconic red bullseye? Well, my vision is a bit like that. The central part, the red bullseye, that’s my missing central vision. I can’t see things right in front of me. It’s like trying to focus on something that’s just not there.

And then there’s the peripheral vision, the red part that surrounds the bullseye. I don’t have that either. Everything around me is like a blurry, undefined space. I can’t see what’s happening to the side, which can be challenging when navigating the world.

Now, that white space in between, where it’s clear in the Target logo, that’s the part of my vision that’s slowly closing in due to my degenerative eye disease. It’s fuzzy and constantly changing. The red parts, they’re black and gone for me. It’s a reality I face every day. When things , objects , people are moving my vision that is left can not focus. It’s like a kaleidoscope.

But here’s the thing, even though my sight will be completely gone, I’m working toward continuing my true vision and passion. My diagnosis is degenerative, so there will be no more white spots. I’m living with blindness, and that’s not the end of my story. I intend to keep pursuing my dreams, my passions, and my true vision of a fulfilling life.

So, when you think of my blindness, think of that Target logo, and remember that despite the challenges, I’m here, I’m strong, and I’m determined to embrace every moment and keep living my life to the fullest. 💪❤️ Thank you for being a part of my journey.

🌟Imposter Syndrome🌟

Hey there, friends! 👋 I’ve got a question for you today:
are used to think of imposter syndrome as a weakness of my own character.

Have you ever battled Imposter Syndrome, and have you felt this in your relationships too? Share your thoughts below!

You know, life has thrown me some incredible curveballs, from my journey as a Paralympic skier to a blind adventurer. 🎿🏔️ But one challenge that often stayed hidden in the shadows was Imposter Syndrome. 🙈

Imposter Syndrome can creep into the minds of the most accomplished individuals, making us doubt our abilities, feel like frauds, and question our achievements. 🤷‍♀️ It used to have a tight grip on me, making me question whether I truly deserved my successes.

Being the first blind contestant on TV show Dancing with the Stars was one of my hardest battles with Imposter Syndrome. I mean, imagine the doubts that raced through my mind – “Can I really do this? Am I worthy of this platform?” 🕺💃

But here’s the thing – it’s okay to feel this way sometimes. It’s a reminder that we’re pushing boundaries, stepping out of our comfort zones, and aiming higher. 🚀

For me, I don’t think it’s something I will overcome completely, but I embrace that this uncertainty will show up, and I remind myself that it’s a part of my journey. 🌟

So, if you ever find yourself battling Imposter Syndrome, know that you’re not alone. Remember that your journey is uniquely yours, and your achievements are a testament to your hard work and dedication. 🌈

Let’s support one another, share our stories, and celebrate our victories – big and small. Together, we can conquer self-doubt and reach for the stars. 🌠✨

🌟MS: An Invisible Battle🌟

I want to share something deeply personal, something I haven’t talked about much. It’s about my journey with Multiple Sclerosis (MS). 🧡 MS is often referred to as an invisible disease, and for me, it truly is. You see, being blind is just one part of my life, but living with MS adds a layer of complexity that’s hard to put into words. It’s been one of the toughest challenges I’ve faced. 🌧️
And for those of you wondering, yes, I do have lesions on my brain, including a new one that appeared on my right frontal lobe just two months ago. It’s a reminder that MS is unpredictable, but it won’t deter me from living my life to the fullest. 
I wake up somedays in a fog, feeling tired beyond words. Some days, it’s a monumental task just to get out of bed. But I keep pushing forward because I believe in the power of resilience and mobility. 💪

One of the most challenging aspects of MS, for me, is its impact on my speech. There are days when I struggle to get the words out, when my thoughts feel trapped, and I can’t say what I want to say. Public speaking, which is a big part of my life, can become a battleground with this disease. 

But I’ve learned to own it, to stand up and explain to others that this disease, which affects my brain and the communication pathways within it, can sometimes take control. It doesn’t define me, but it’s a part of my journey. 🧠

I share this not for pity, but to raise awareness about MS and to let others who may be silently battling it know that they are not alone. We are warriors, each with our unique battles, and together, we can overcome anything. 
Thank you for being a part of my journey, for your support, and for allowing me to be authentically me. Let’s keep fighting, keep supporting one another, and keep embracing every aspect of our lives. 🌈✨

🌟Vulnerability 🌟

I want to share something deeply personal—my journey with vulnerability. It’s a feeling we all experience, a reminder of our humanity and imperfections. 

In my own journey, vulnerability has been a constant companion. There have been times when I’ve felt less-than, not enough, because of my blindness. There have been days when I questioned my worth and my abilities. And, yes, vulnerability has reared its head in my life because of my battle with Multiple Sclerosis. It’s a silent struggle that’s often overlooked. 

But here’s the truth: Vulnerability doesn’t define me, or any of us. We’re not the sum of our mistakes or the actions of others. We’re defined by our resilience, our courage, and our capacity for growth. 🌟

Today, I’m opening up about something I’ve never discussed before, out of shame and fear. I’ve been a victim of both mental and physical abuse. It’s time to break the silence and release the grip of vulnerability. 
This revelation isn’t about pity; it’s a testament to the strength within all of us. It’s a reminder that vulnerability can be a source of power when we choose to share and heal. 

Let’s start a heartfelt conversation about vulnerability. Share your experiences, your stories of healing, or how you’ve learned to embrace it in your own life. Together, we can break free from the chains that bind us and find self-acceptance and love. ❤️

Good news!! 🐾 ❤️

 invite you all to join me on this adventure as I share my experiences as a puppy raiser. It's a path filled with love, challenges, and learning, and I couldn't be more excited. I'm also open to any help or advice from you all, so feel free to share your insights and thoughts as we move forward.
